 (11,'http://singaporestockmarketnews.blogspot.com/2015/02/yangzijiang-shipbuilding-higher-dps.html','singaporestockmarketnews.blogspot.com','http://feeds.feedburner.com/blogspot/wKTe','Singapore Stock Market News','Yangzijiang Shipbuilding - Higher DPS','Yangzijiang Shipbuilding - Higher DPS','2015-02-27 18:44:00','0','1','blogs','US','0','','â–  FY14 core PATMI beat expectations â–  Final DPS higher at 5.5 Scts, from 5 Scts last year â–  Recent award of order for LNG carriers raises Yangzijiangâ€™s profile as a top notch shipbuilder â–  Maintain BUY; TP S$1.62 Highlights FY14 results above â–  At first glance, FY14 headline PATMI of Rmb3.48bn (+13% y-o-y) was largely in line with expectations . However, this included a Rmb315m additional provision for Held-to-Maturity (HTM) investments in 4Q14, as management prudently raised the impairment from 5% to 15% for HTM investments exposed to the property sector (c.32% of total portfolio) . The writedown of raw material inventories was net off by recognition of forfeited deposits for cancelled vessels two years back. Stripping the provision out, FY14 PATMI would have been Rmb3.79bn, 6%/13% above our/consensusâ€™ estimates. Yangzijiang declared 5.5 Scts final DPS (higher than last yearâ€™s 5 Scts), implying 4.4% yield . Healthy margins â–  Shipbuilding gross margin moderated 3.5ppts q-o-q to 17.5% in 4Q, due largely to maiden recognition of a jack up project (60% in 4Q14) at cost in that quarter. Full year shipbuilding gross margin was around 20%. Strong balance sheet â–  Including HTM investments, Yangzjiang is in net cash, equivalent to 29 Scts per share or 23% of its NTA . Outlook Set to outperform peers â–  Yangzijiang is set to outperform peers with 5- to 10-ppt higher margins (through better newbuild prices, payment terms and efficiency as well as active cash management) and relatively stable profits with upside potential from the recognition of relocation fees from the government (Rmb720m) and profits from disposal of previously cancelled vessels of c.Rmb600m. Divestment of non-core assets â–  Yangzijiang is paring down its non-core investments as promised. HTM investments have reduced to Rmb10.8bn, from Rmb13.0bn in mid-2014. This is expected to be further scaled back to less than Rmb10bn by end-2015. It has also divested c.Rmb1.8bn worth of property projects since 2Q14 and targets to divest the remaining Rmb1.5bn (excluding old yard redevelopment of approx. Rmb1.4bn) in the near future. Climbing up the value chain â–  Yangzijiang has secured US$135m worth of orders to build two 27.5k cbm LNG carriers in mid-Feb, marking its first foray into this sophisticated vessel market, long dominated by Korean peers . The group recorded decent order wins of US$1.8bn in 2014, bringing orderbook to US$4.62bn as of end 2014. This translates into a healthy book-to-bill of 1.9x. Management aims to secure US$2bn worth of orders this year . Technical Analysis Daily Chart Valuation We value Yangzijiang based on sum-of-the-parts (SOTP) methodology, to better reflect the valuation for its various segments . We arrive at a target price of S$1.62 , after applying 8x FY15F price earnings (PE) on shipbuilding earnings, 0.5x price-to-book value (P/BV) for bulk carriers, 1x P/BV for investments, and 25% discount to net present value (NPV) of its property project. Risks Prolonged industry downturn â–  While we believe the worst is over for the shipbuilding industry, in the event of unforeseen circumstances that lead to a prolonged downturn, Yangzijiangâ€™s earnings and share price will be adversely affected. Spike in steel price â–  Steel cost accounts for 20-25% of COGS . We estimate that every 1% increase in steel cost could reduce net profit by 1.1%. ( Read Report ) Source : DBS Group Research'),
 (12,'http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/shaking-up-the-management-what-is-in-store-for-standard-chartered/articleshow/46389785.cms','economictimes.indiatimes.com','','','Shaking up the management: What is in store for Standard Chartered? - The Economic Times','Shaking up the management: What is in store for Standard Chartered? - The Economic Times','2015-02-27 08:00:00','0','0','news','','0','http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/thumb/msid-46389808,width-310,resizemode-4/shaking-up-the-management-what-is-in-store-for-standard-chartered.jpg','What\'s buzzing hot on Budget 2015? Check out our in-depth coverage MUMBAI: Whenever an enterprise is in trouble, it is not unusual for vultures to circle it. Will it be different for Standard Chartered where shareholders have prevailed in overthrowing the management? What is in store for the Asia-focused lender? That the first step in shaking up the management has been done, the choice of replacement for chief executive Peter Sands , Bill Winters, formerly of JPMorgan Chase , has led to speculation as to the direction he could choose to steer the bank. The options are that either Winters goes through the painful process of weeding out the bad bank, and rebuild it for it to stand on its own legs over many years. Or indulge in cosmetic changes for a few quarters with drastic cost cuts and sell it off to a CEO who is desperate to get bigger in Asia irrespective of the dented business. Winters made his name in the investment banking business of JPMorgan before breaking with Jamie Dimon. To rebuild the business, he has to focus on Indian operations which was once its best, but has fallen on bad times. The 2005 acquisition of Korea First Bank for $3.3 billion has also become sour and needs to be sold off, say analysts. \"There is nothing as a good or a bad deal,\" said the head of an international bank who did not want to be identified. \"Standard Chartered Bank\'s balance sheet is stressed. At the right price, global banks wanting to increase their presence in Asia could consider the option.\" But the question is which global bank will tread into Asia - a bit part of it is India and China - when many have already burnt their fingers and retreated. The US banks wouldn\'t want to get into Asian retail business, and so is the case with European giants such as Credit Agricole , Deutsche Bank or others, said analysts. \"We decline to comment on speculation,\" said a Standard Chartered spokesperson. \"In terms of strategy, we will be updating the market next week as part of our results.\" Even if Western banks are not interested, The Australia New Zealand Banking Group or others from the region which are expanding in Asia could be interested. But even they are focusing more on corporate business, rather than chasing the consumer wallet. The fact that Temasek Holdings , the government of Singapore\'s investment company, is the single-largest shareholder in Standard Chartered as well as DBS Group Holdings has prompted some to expect that the investor could work out a strategy to combine the two. \"A transaction of this nature would be very complicated and distract us from our current growth strategy. Hence, it is not on our agenda at this time,\" DBS said, in an email response. Whether Winters decides to trim Standard Chartered to make it a profitable bank, or sells it to a desperate CEO to get bigger, Temasek will have the final say. DON\'T MISS any stories, follow us on Twitter Follow '),
