 (16,'http://www.businesstimes.com.sg/banking-finance/dbs-hires-rabobanks-shome-as-india-ceo','www.businesstimes.com.sg','','','DBS hires Rabobank\'s Shome as India CEO, Banking & Finance - THE BUSINESS TIMES','DBS hires Rabobank\'s Shome as India CEO, Banking & Finance - THE BUSINESS TIMES','2015-02-28 08:00:00','0','0','news','','0','http://www.businesstimes.com.sg/sites/all/themes/custom/businesstimes/images/BTflipboard2.jpg','DBS hires Rabobank\'s Shome as India CEO He will replace Sanjiv Bhasin from April 15; appointment comes after surge in soured debt; 28 Feb 5:50 AM \nMumbai \nDBS Group Holdings Ltd has hired Rabobank NA\'s Surojit Shome to replace Sanjiv Bhasin as head of its Indian operations after a surge in soured debt. Mr Shome, who was Rabobank\'s India chief executive officer and country head, will join DBS as CEO of its Indian business effective '),
 (17,'http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/banking/finance/sanjiv-bhasin-quits-as-dbs-india-head/articleshow/46405265.cms','economictimes.indiatimes.com','http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/industry/banking/finance/industry/banking/finance/rssfeeds/13358311.cms','Finance-Banking/Finance-Industry-The Economic Times','Sanjiv Bhasin quits as DBS India head','Sanjiv Bhasin quits as DBS India head','2015-02-28 13:14:00','0','0','blogs','IL','0','http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/thumb/msid-46405340,width-310,resizemode-4/sanjiv-bhasin-quits-as-dbs-india-head.jpg','Sanjiv Bhasin quits as DBS India head By ET Bureau | 28 Feb, 2015, 10.44AM IST What\'s buzzing hot on Budget 2015? Check out our in-depth coverage DBS India head Sanjiv Bhasin has resigned for personal reasons and will be replaced by Surojit Shome, who quit as chief executive of Rabobank earlier this month. Bhasin, who turned 60 this month, plans to pursue different interests, Singapore headquartered DBS Bank said in a statement on Friday. His seven-year stint will end on June 30, it added. \"Shome, CEO and country head of Rabobank India, will assume the role of CEO of DBS India with effect from April 15,\" the bank said. DBS Group Holdings, Southeast Asia\'s largest lender, posted its lowest quarterly profit at the end of December 2014 in more than two years, as trading income slumped and provisions for bad loans increased. The bank, which has 12 branches in the country, has seen a 46% dip in profits to Rs 299.2 crore at the end of March 2014 compared with Rs 554.5 crore last year. The bank\'s stressed assets in the small and medium enterprises business has led to a steep rise in its bad loans. Non-performing loans of the bank more than doubled to 10.19% at the end of March 2014 compared with 2.37% last year. Shome, who has worked with Lehman Brothers and Citigroup, faces the challenge of cleaning up DBS\' India book and bring growth back to the balance sheet. Globally, investors and shareholders are increasingly becoming intolerant towards bank managements and boards, with depressed profitability following slowdown in growth markets like India. On Thursday, London-headquartered Asia centric Standard Chartered saw a management reshuffle with the exit of Peter Sands, its chief executive officer, and Asia head Jaspal Bindra. Bill Winters, a former JPMorgan Chase investment banker, was appointed the new chief executive of the UK bank. DON\'T MISS any stories, follow us on Twitter Follow');
